      {
         "id": "SECTION_game",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Clapping\n\nWhen we clap, we generate a sound. This sound depends on the speed with which we bring our hands together. Furthermore, we can clap repeatedly, creating rhythms that help us compose music.\n\nThis act of clapping is directly linked to different cultures, and is even used in games that aid people's intellectual development. One of the cultures where we can observe the use of this resource in teaching is the Shona culture in Zimbabwe (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nIn this text, we will take the first steps in using clapping in learning. Next, choose the number of times the hands will clap. Then, choose the speed of the claps and a color for the hands. **Note that, regardless of the color chosen, the claps will be the same, because we are all equal, regardless of our color** (<htcite3>; <htcite4>). We are all equal because we emerged in Africa approximately 300,000 years ago (<htcite5>). The different skin colors are basically due to the amount of melanin populations have and the environment in which they live, with darker skin being predominant in regions near the equator —the imaginary line that divides the Earth's sphere in half— and lighter skin in more distant regions (<htcite6>).\n\nFinally, press the play button (<i class=\"fa-solid fa-play\" onclick=\"startClap()\" style=\"font-size:1em;color:#0f0;\" ></i>) and repeat the claps.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "31070f9b-d4f7-46ed-8ca3-88dd8dee793c",
                     "text": "Nyota, S., & Mapara, J.",
